description: Developed multi-INT sensor resource management algorithms which produced optimal, synchronized C4ISR collection plans and sensor schedules). This tool maximizes target collection value subject to tasking and platform collection performance estimates and constraints over planning horizons of typically up to 24 hours in duration. These constraints typically included collection time windows, collection quality, operating/no fly zones, and threat exposure. These systems include high altitude airborne platforms, standoff collectors, medium-to-low altitude UAVs and space borne platforms, and include a mix of sensors such as ELINT, COMINT, IMINT (EO/IR) and SAR/GMTI radar. Specifically, he implemented and tested high fidelity geolocation models (AOA, TDOA, FDOA) together with these planning algorithms. He also investigated transitioning this planning tool to several programs including Space Radar, the MC2A/E-10A next-generation sensor platform, the Distributed Common Ground System, as well as various overhead sensor system architectures. As Principal Investigator for a Phase II Small Business Innovative Research (SBIR) effort, integrated the above planning tool with a Multiple Hypothesis Tracker used for ground moving targets with MTI Radar sensors. The tracker/sensor resource manager component generates task cues for the planning component, which, in turn, provides updated platform routes to the sensor resource manager. As Principal Investigator for another Phase II SBIR, investigated the use of hierarchical target valuation algorithms based for both Level I and II fusion information (groups of objects, such as convoys) in a sensor resource manager, which chooses both sensor pointing direction and mode (MTI, HRR, SAR) based on future sensor/state predictions provided by Finite State Markov models. He also produced an algorithm description document for a multiple-platform SIGINT AOA geolocation algorithm and produced a prototype version of this algorithm in MATLAB.
